chapter1 = "<h5>What is SQL</h5><ul><li>SQL stands for Structured Query Language</li><li>SQL designed to manipulate data in Relational Database System</li></ul><h5>Basic terminologies used in SQL</h5><ul><li>Database: Collection of tables/entities</li><li>Table: Collection of related information having rows and columns</li><li>Record: Row of the table or individual entry present in the table</li><li>Column: Contains all information related to specific attribute or field in table</li></ul><h5>SQL Language has several categories: </h5><ul><li>Data Definition Language (DDL): Commands for defining relation schemas, deleting relations, and modifying relation schemas</li><li>Data Manipulation Language (DML): Provides the ability to query information from the database and to insert tuples into, delete tuples from, and modify tuples in the database</li><li>Transaction Control Language (TCL): Commands are basically used for managing and controlling the transactions </li></ul>"

chapter2 = "<h2> Table  creation </h2><p>In SQL , everything revolve around tables. Lets take a look how can we create tables</p><b> Syntax:</b><p> create table (column1 datatype1, column2 datatype2......., constraint1, constraint2....) </p><b>Example</b><p> Suppose you want to save data related to students in database. So you decide to create a new table for student</p><b>Lets divide this process in 3 phases</b><p> <b>Step 1</b>: Analyse information which we would like to store in database</p><p> Following information of student which we want to save :- First name, Last name, city, id </p><p> <b>Step 2</b>: Identify data type, constraints/validations on the fields</p><table><tr><th>Field</th><th>Data type</th></tr><tr><td>First name</td><td>varchar(255)</td></tr><tr><td>Last name</td><td>varchar(255)</td></tr><tr><td>City</td><td>varchar(255)</td></tr><tr><td>id</td><td>int</td></tr></table><br><p><b>Step 3</b>: Create database schema based on the information collected in above steps</p><p> Following query will create a new table in database: </p><p>create table student (first_name varchar(255), last_name varchar(255), city varchar(255), id int);</p><p>Bingooooooo!!! You have successfully added a new table in database</p>"

chapter3 = "<h2>Table Creation with different variations</h2><h5>Create table with primary key</h5><p>Each and every table should have primary key. Let's check how to create table with primary key</p><b> Syntax:</b><p>create table (column1 datatype1, column2 datatype2......., primary key(column_name));</p><p>Let's gather following information about student and then create table schema</p><table><tr><th>Field</th><th>Data type</th><th>Is Primary Key?</th><th>Is Required?</th></tr><tr><td>id</td><td>int</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>First name</td><td>varchar(255)</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Last name</td><td>varchar(255)</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>City</td><td>varchar(255)</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr></table><br /><p>Following query will create brand new table with primary key:</p><p>create table student (id int, first_name varchar(255) not null, last_name varchar(255) not null, city varchar(255), primary key(id));</p><p>Student table has 4  columns: id, first_name, last_name, city</p><p>id column is primary key of  student table. Each table should have primmary key which uniquely identifies each and every row in table.</p><p>As per given information, first name, last name and city are required fields. Not null constraint ensures that there is no null value stored in these fields.</p> <h5>Create table with auto-increment primary key</h5><p>Each and every table should have primary key. Let's check how to create table with primary key</p><b> Syntax:</b><p>create table (column1 datatype1 AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY, column2 datatype2.......);</p><p> Let's try to create student table with information we have in earlier step</p><p>Following query will create brand new table with auto-increment primary key:</p><p>create table student (id int AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY, first_name varchar(255) not null, last_name varchar(255) not null, city varchar(255));</p><p>Student table has 4  columns: id, first_name, last_name, city</p><p>id column is primary key of  student table. Each table should have primmary key which uniquely identifies each and every row in table.</p><p>As per given information, first name, last name and city are required fields. Not null constraint ensures that there is no null value stored in these fields.</p> <p>The data type of id (PK) is integer and it is followed by auto increment keyword. It means that when  youu  insert row into table without providing value of id, Postgres system  will generate integer value for that column.</p>"

